  • The Google Nest Temperature Sensor (2nd gen) makes it easy to manage hot and cold spots throughout your home[1]; put it in any room to get the right temperature, right where you want it
  • Its simple to set up and control in the Google Home or Nest app; just use the app to set the temperature a room should reach at a certain time of day
  • The battery lasts up to 3 years, so you can put it on a wall, shelf, or wherever you want[2]
  • You can place Nest Temperature Sensors in up to six rooms for maximum comfort; prioritize the temperature of one room, or create an average temperature across them, like bedrooms[1,3]
  • The Nest Temperature Sensor (2nd gen) works with the Nest Learning Thermostat (4th gen), Nest Learning Thermostat (3rd gen), and Nest Thermostat E[1,4]
  • Sleek and simple, the Nest Temperature Sensor (2nd gen) fits right in wherever you place it[1]

Additional details

The Nest Temperature Sensor (2nd gen) makes it easy to manage hot and cold spots throughout your home. Just put it in a preferred room and get the right temp right where you want it. Its battery powered, so you can set it, then forget its even there.[1] And it works with the Nest Learning Thermostat (4th gen), Nest Learning Thermostat (3rd gen), and Nest Thermostat E.[1,4] LEGAL [1] Nest thermostat sold separately. [2] Approximate battery life based on testing conducted in Taiwan in 2024 on pre-production hardware and software. Actual battery life may vary. [3] Google Home app required. See here for details (g.co/nest/tempsensorapp). [4] Some features are limited to the Google Home app. 5] Remote control requires working internet and Wi-Fi.

Customers find the temperature sensor helps monitor temperatures throughout their house and works well for balancing temperatures. Moreover, the device is easy to set up, sleek in design, and helps save on energy costs. However, the battery life and connectivity receive mixed feedback.   • SEVENTH HEAVEN
    4.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    Nice upgrade from the previous version.
    Reviewed in Canada on November 5, 2024
    1.
    If you have a Google nest thermostat that is compatible with these sensors and can justify the average of $50 per cents cost then these might actually be something that can improve your heating and cooling needs in your house, granted you follow the instructions and use... See more
    If you have a Google nest thermostat that is compatible with these sensors and can justify the average of $50 per cents cost then these might actually be something that can improve your heating and cooling needs in your house, granted you follow the instructions and use them as their intended to be used. The trick with these sensors is to see which room or rooms have a much different temperature than the rest of them and then you open and close your vent registers as needed to average it out. For example, if your bedroom is 5 more than your living room, close your bedroom register and keep your living room register open. This will force more air to the room that is needed. Caution note, however: try different variations and monitor overtime to be on the safe side as if you have a lot of events closed and one open it may get too hot in one room or another. It takes some back-and-forth and different trial and error periods. After fiddling with it for quite some time, you should see a little bit of a difference or a lot, depending on the difference in temperature and the type of vents that are installed in your house. Theyre easy to pair to the Google home app, which is also set up to my Alexa app, but it only lets me control the main thermostat through Alexa not the individual sensors. Overall worked well for us so we can regulator house, but its very expensive, especially if you have several
